I really love reverse clashes! This one is really cool,  you understand what to do very quickly. I agree with @VinceMC: the solution isn't that difficult, but it takes time to write it and make it work correctly. Personally, it took me about 14 minutes (with a stopwatch) to finish it.
Despite all of that, I think it's a good clash because it forces us to code under pressure. The example is clear enough that we quickly understand what to do, and so, all the available time is spent coding the solution.
Here's mine (Python3):

w, h = [int(i) for i in input().split()]
grid = []
check = set()
spot = None
for y in range(h):
    line = []
    for x, c in enumerate(input()):
        line.append(c)
        if len(check) == 0:
            check.add(c)
        elif c not in check:
            check.add(c)
            if (x,y) == (1,0):
                spot = (0,0)
            else:
                spot = (x,y)
    grid.append(line)

if spot != None:
    x,y = spot
    for dx, dy, c in {(0,-1,'v'),(0,-2,'|'),(0,1,'^'),(0,2,'|'),(1,0,'<'),(2,0,'-'),(-1,0,'>'),(-2,0,'-')}:
        nx, ny = x+dx, y+dy
        if 0 <= nx < w and 0 <= ny < h:
            grid[ny][nx] = c
for line in grid:
    print(''.join(line))

Wow! Cool concept! It was very fun to solve, but unfortunately, it took more than 15 minutes for me to code my solution (in Python3). I'm not even a noob either, so if it took that long for me, then imagine all the beginners who would struggle so badly when they play this. Maybe I just suck, but this might be too hard for most. Nonetheless, the concept is really nice!

